{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"I just heard the best joke about Bond Emeruwa."},{"time":3000,"text":"I was having lunch with him just a few minutes ago,"},{"time":6000,"text":"and a Nigerian journalist comes -- and this will only make sense"},{"time":8000,"text":"if you've ever watched a James Bond movie --"},{"time":11000,"text":"and a Nigerian journalist comes up to him and goes,"},{"time":13000,"text":"\"Aha, we meet again, Mr. Bond!\""},{"time":16000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":18000,"text":"It was great."}]},{"cues":[{"time":19000,"text":"So, I've got a little sheet of paper here,"},{"time":23000,"text":"mostly because I'm Nigerian and if you leave me alone,"},{"time":25000,"text":"I'll talk for like two hours."}]},{"cues":[{"time":27000,"text":"I just want to say good afternoon, good evening."},{"time":33000,"text":"It's been an incredible few days."},{"time":35000,"text":"It's downhill from now on. I wanted to thank Emeka and Chris."},{"time":38000,"text":"But also, most importantly, all the invisible people behind TED"},{"time":42000,"text":"that you just see flitting around the whole place"},{"time":45000,"text":"that have made sort of this space for such a diverse and robust conversation."},{"time":51000,"text":"It's really amazing."},{"time":54000,"text":"I've been in the audience."},{"time":56000,"text":"I'm a writer, and I've been watching people with the slide shows"},{"time":60000,"text":"and scientists and bankers, and I've been feeling a bit"},{"time":64000,"text":"like a gangsta rapper at a bar mitzvah."},{"time":67000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":69000,"text":"Like, what have I got to say about all this?"},{"time":73000,"text":"And I was watching Jane [Goodall] yesterday,"},{"time":75000,"text":"and I thought it was really great, and I was watching"},{"time":77000,"text":"those incredible slides of the chimpanzees, and I thought,"},{"time":81000,"text":"\"Wow. What if a chimpanzee could talk, you know? What would it say?\""},{"time":86000,"text":"My first thought was, \"Well, you know, there's George Bush.\""},{"time":88000,"text":"But then I thought, \"Why be rude to chimpanzees?\""},{"time":94000,"text":"I guess there goes my green card."},{"time":96000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":98000,"text":"There's been a lot of talk about narrative in Africa."},{"time":101000,"text":"And what's become increasingly clear to me is that"},{"time":105000,"text":"we're talking about news stories about Africa;"},{"time":108000,"text":"we're not really talking about African narratives."},{"time":110000,"text":"And it's important to make a distinction, because if the news is anything to go by,"},{"time":114000,"text":"40 percent of Americans can't -- either can't afford health insurance"},{"time":120000,"text":"or have the most inadequate health insurance,"},{"time":123000,"text":"and have a president who, despite the protest"},{"time":126000,"text":"of millions of his citizens -- even his own Congress --"},{"time":129000,"text":"continues to prosecute a senseless war."},{"time":132000,"text":"So if news is anything to go by,"},{"time":134000,"text":"the U.S. is right there with Zimbabwe, right?"},{"time":137000,"text":"Which it isn't really, is it?"},{"time":141000,"text":"And talking about war, my girlfriend has this great t-shirt"},{"time":143000,"text":"that says, \"Bombing for peace is like fucking for virginity.\""},{"time":148000,"text":"It's amazing, isn't it?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":151000,"text":"The truth is, everything we know about America,"},{"time":160000,"text":"everything Americans come to know about being American,"},{"time":162000,"text":"isn't from the news."},{"time":164000,"text":"I live there."},{"time":166000,"text":"We don't go home at the end of the day and think,"},{"time":168000,"text":"\"Well, I really know who I am now"},{"time":169000,"text":"because the Wall Street Journal says that the Stock Exchange"},{"time":173000,"text":"closed at this many points.\""},{"time":175000,"text":"What we know about how to be who we are comes from stories."},{"time":178000,"text":"It comes from the novels, the movies, the fashion magazines."},{"time":181000,"text":"It comes from popular culture."}]},{"cues":[{"time":183000,"text":"In other words, it's the agents of our imagination"},{"time":185000,"text":"who really shape who we are. And this is important to remember,"},{"time":189000,"text":"because in Africa"},{"time":192000,"text":"the complicated questions we want to ask about"},{"time":196000,"text":"what all of this means has been asked"},{"time":198000,"text":"from the rock paintings of the San people,"},{"time":202000,"text":"through the Sundiata epics of Mali, to modern contemporary literature."},{"time":206000,"text":"If you want to know about Africa, read our literature --"},{"time":209000,"text":"and not just \"Things Fall Apart,\" because that would be like saying,"},{"time":213000,"text":"\"I've read 'Gone with the Wind' and so I know everything about America.\""},{"time":217000,"text":"That's very important."},{"time":219000,"text":"There's a poem by Jack Gilbert called \"The Forgotten Dialect of the Heart.\""},{"time":223000,"text":"He says, \"When the Sumerian tablets were first translated,"},{"time":228000,"text":"they were thought to be business records."},{"time":231000,"text":"But what if they were poems and psalms?"},{"time":233000,"text":"My love is like twelve Ethiopian goats"},{"time":237000,"text":"standing still in the morning light."},{"time":241000,"text":"Shiploads of thuja are what my body wants to say to your body."},{"time":246000,"text":"Giraffes are this desire in the dark.\""},{"time":250000,"text":"This is important."}]},{"cues":[{"time":251000,"text":"It's important because misreading is really the chance"},{"time":254000,"text":"for complication and opportunity."},{"time":256000,"text":"The first Igbo Bible was translated from English"},{"time":260000,"text":"in about the 1800s by Bishop Crowther,"},{"time":262000,"text":"who was a Yoruba."},{"time":263000,"text":"And it's important to know Igbo is a tonal language,"},{"time":266000,"text":"and so they'll say the word \"igwe\" and \"igwe\":"},{"time":270000,"text":"same spelling, one means \"sky\" or \"heaven,\""},{"time":274000,"text":"and one means \"bicycle\" or \"iron.\""},{"time":277000,"text":"So \"God is in heaven surrounded by His angels\""},{"time":281000,"text":"was translated as --"},{"time":283000,"text":"[Igbo]."},{"time":287000,"text":"And for some reason, in Cameroon, when they tried"},{"time":289000,"text":"to translate the Bible into Cameroonian patois,"},{"time":291000,"text":"they chose the Igbo version."},{"time":293000,"text":"And I'm not going to give you the patois translation;"},{"time":295000,"text":"I'm going to make it standard English."},{"time":296000,"text":"Basically, it ends up as \"God is on a bicycle with his angels.\""},{"time":303000,"text":"This is good, because language complicates things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":308000,"text":"You know, we often think that language mirrors"},{"time":310000,"text":"the world in which we live, and I find that's not true."},{"time":314000,"text":"The language actually makes the world in which we live."},{"time":319000,"text":"Language is not -- I mean, things don't have"},{"time":321000,"text":"any mutable value by themselves; we ascribe them a value."},{"time":324000,"text":"And language can't be understood in its abstraction."},{"time":327000,"text":"It can only be understood in the context of story,"},{"time":329000,"text":"and everything, all of this is story."},{"time":333000,"text":"And it's important to remember that,"},{"time":335000,"text":"because if we don't, then we become ahistorical."},{"time":339000,"text":"We've had a lot of -- a parade of amazing ideas here."},{"time":342000,"text":"But these are not new to Africa."},{"time":344000,"text":"Nigeria got its independence in 1960."},{"time":347000,"text":"The first time the possibility for independence was discussed"},{"time":351000,"text":"was in 1922, following the Aba women's market riots."},{"time":355000,"text":"In 1967, in the middle of the Biafran-Nigerian Civil War,"},{"time":359000,"text":"Dr. Njoku-Obi invented the Cholera vaccine."},{"time":363000,"text":"So, you know, the thing is to remember that"},{"time":365000,"text":"because otherwise, 10 years from now,"},{"time":367000,"text":"we'll be back here trying to tell this story again."}]},{"cues":[{"time":371000,"text":"So, what it says to me then is that it's not really --"},{"time":376000,"text":"the problem isn't really the stories that are being told"},{"time":378000,"text":"or which stories are being told,"},{"time":380000,"text":"the problem really is the terms of humanity"},{"time":383000,"text":"that we're willing to bring to complicate every story,"},{"time":386000,"text":"and that's really what it's all about."},{"time":389000,"text":"Let me tell you a Nigerian joke."},{"time":391000,"text":"Well, it's just a joke, anyway."},{"time":393000,"text":"So there's Tom, Dick and Harry and they're working construction."},{"time":397000,"text":"And Tom opens up his lunch box and there's rice in it,"},{"time":400000,"text":"and he goes on this rant about, \"Twenty years,"},{"time":402000,"text":"my wife has been packing rice for lunch."},{"time":404000,"text":"If she does it again tomorrow, I'm going to throw myself"},{"time":406000,"text":"off this building and kill myself.\""},{"time":408000,"text":"And Dick and Harry repeat this."},{"time":410000,"text":"The next day, Tom opens his lunchbox, there's rice,"},{"time":412000,"text":"so he throws himself off and kills himself,"},{"time":414000,"text":"and Tom, Dick and Harry follow."},{"time":416000,"text":"And now the inquest -- you know, Tom's wife"},{"time":418000,"text":"and Dick's wife are distraught."},{"time":419000,"text":"They wished they'd not packed rice."},{"time":421000,"text":"But Harry's wife is confused, because she said, \"You know,"},{"time":424000,"text":"Harry had been packing his own lunch for 20 years.\""},{"time":427000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":431000,"text":"This seemingly innocent joke, when I heard it as a child in Nigeria,"},{"time":436000,"text":"was told about Igbo, Yoruba and Hausa,"},{"time":438000,"text":"with the Hausa being Harry."},{"time":440000,"text":"So what seems like an eccentric if tragic joke about Harry"},{"time":444000,"text":"becomes a way to spread ethnic hatred."},{"time":448000,"text":"My father was educated in Cork, in the University of Cork, in the '50s."},{"time":452000,"text":"In fact, every time I read in Ireland,"},{"time":454000,"text":"people get me all mistaken and they say,"},{"time":456000,"text":"\"Oh, this is Chris O'Barney from Cork.\""},{"time":458000,"text":"But he was also in Oxford in the '50s,"},{"time":462000,"text":"and yet growing up as a child in Nigeria,"},{"time":464000,"text":"my father used to say to me, \"You must never eat or drink"},{"time":467000,"text":"in a Yoruba person's house because they will poison you.\""},{"time":472000,"text":"It makes sense now when I think about it,"},{"time":474000,"text":"because if you'd known my father,"},{"time":475000,"text":"you would've wanted to poison him too."},{"time":478000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":483000,"text":"So I was born in 1966, at the beginning"},{"time":487000,"text":"of the Biafran-Nigerian Civil War, and the war ended after three years."},{"time":493000,"text":"And I was growing up in school and the federal government"},{"time":496000,"text":"didn't want us taught about the history of the war,"},{"time":499000,"text":"because they thought it probably would make us"},{"time":502000,"text":"generate a new generation of rebels."},{"time":504000,"text":"So I had a very inventive teacher, a Pakistani Muslim,"},{"time":507000,"text":"who wanted to teach us about this."},{"time":509000,"text":"So what he did was to teach us Jewish Holocaust history,"},{"time":513000,"text":"and so huddled around books with photographs of people in Auschwitz,"},{"time":518000,"text":"I learned the melancholic history of my people"},{"time":521000,"text":"through the melancholic history of another people."},{"time":523000,"text":"I mean, picture this -- really picture this."},{"time":525000,"text":"A Pakistani Muslim teaching Jewish Holocaust history"},{"time":530000,"text":"to young Igbo children."}]},{"cues":[{"time":531000,"text":"Story is powerful."},{"time":533000,"text":"Story is fluid and it belongs to nobody."},{"time":535000,"text":"And it should come as no surprise"},{"time":537000,"text":"that my first novel at 16 was about Neo-Nazis"},{"time":540000,"text":"taking over Nigeria to institute the Fourth Reich."},{"time":543000,"text":"It makes perfect sense."},{"time":544000,"text":"And they were to blow up strategic targets"},{"time":548000,"text":"and take over the country, and they were foiled"},{"time":550000,"text":"by a Nigerian James Bond called Coyote Williams,"},{"time":554000,"text":"and a Jewish Nazi hunter."},{"time":557000,"text":"And it happened over four continents."},{"time":558000,"text":"And when the book came out, I was heralded as Africa's answer"},{"time":561000,"text":"to Frederick Forsyth, which is a dubious honor at best."},{"time":565000,"text":"But also, the book was launched in time for me to be accused"},{"time":568000,"text":"of constructing the blueprint for a foiled coup attempt."},{"time":572000,"text":"So at 18, I was bonded off to prison in Nigeria."}]},{"cues":[{"time":577000,"text":"I grew up very privileged, and it's important"},{"time":578000,"text":"to talk about privilege, because we don't talk about it here."},{"time":581000,"text":"A lot of us are very privileged."},{"time":583000,"text":"I grew up -- servants, cars, televisions, all that stuff."},{"time":587000,"text":"My story of Nigeria growing up was very different from the story"},{"time":590000,"text":"I encountered in prison, and I had no language for it."},{"time":594000,"text":"I was completely terrified, completely broken,"},{"time":598000,"text":"and kept trying to find a new language,"},{"time":602000,"text":"a new way to make sense of all of this."},{"time":605000,"text":"Six months after that, with no explanation,"},{"time":608000,"text":"they let me go."},{"time":609000,"text":"Now for those of you who have seen me at the buffet tables know"},{"time":611000,"text":"that it was because it was costing them too much to feed me."},{"time":614000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":623000,"text":"But I mean, I grew up with this incredible privilege,"},{"time":625000,"text":"and not just me -- millions of Nigerians"},{"time":627000,"text":"grew up with books and libraries."},{"time":629000,"text":"In fact, we were talking last night about how all"},{"time":633000,"text":"of the steamy novels of Harold Robbins"},{"time":635000,"text":"had done more for sex education of horny teenage boys in Africa"},{"time":639000,"text":"than any sex education programs ever had."},{"time":643000,"text":"All of those are gone."}]},{"cues":[{"time":645000,"text":"We are squandering the most valuable resource"},{"time":647000,"text":"we have on this continent: the valuable resource"},{"time":649000,"text":"of the imagination."},{"time":651000,"text":"In the film, \"Sometimes in April\" by Raoul Peck,"},{"time":654000,"text":"Idris Elba is poised in a scene with his machete raised,"},{"time":658000,"text":"and he's being forced by a crowd to chop up his best friend --"},{"time":662000,"text":"fellow Rwandan Army officer, albeit a Tutsi --"},{"time":665000,"text":"played by Fraser James."},{"time":667000,"text":"And Fraser's on his knees, arms tied behind his back,"},{"time":671000,"text":"and he's crying."},{"time":673000,"text":"He's sniveling."},{"time":674000,"text":"It's a pitiful sight."},{"time":675000,"text":"And as we watch it, we are ashamed."},{"time":680000,"text":"And we want to say to Idris, \"Chop him up."},{"time":683000,"text":"Shut him up.\""},{"time":685000,"text":"And as Idris moves, Fraser screams, \"Stop!"},{"time":689000,"text":"Please stop!\""},{"time":691000,"text":"Idris pauses, then he moves again,"},{"time":694000,"text":"and Fraser says, \"Please!"},{"time":697000,"text":"Please stop!\""},{"time":699000,"text":"And it's not the look of horror and terror on Fraser's face that stops Idris or us;"},{"time":705000,"text":"it's the look in Fraser's eyes."},{"time":707000,"text":"It's one that says, \"Don't do this."},{"time":711000,"text":"And I'm not saying this to save myself,"},{"time":713000,"text":"although this would be nice. I'm doing it to save you,"},{"time":717000,"text":"because if you do this, you will be lost.\""},{"time":721000,"text":"To be so afraid that you're standing in the face"},{"time":724000,"text":"of a death you can't escape and that you're soiling yourself"},{"time":726000,"text":"and crying, but to say in that moment,"},{"time":728000,"text":"as Fraser says to Idris, \"Tell my girlfriend I love her.\""},{"time":732000,"text":"In that moment, Fraser says,"},{"time":736000,"text":"\"I am lost already, but not you ... not you.\""},{"time":741000,"text":"This is a redemption we can all aspire to."}]},{"cues":[{"time":744000,"text":"African narratives in the West, they proliferate."},{"time":748000,"text":"I really don't care anymore."},{"time":749000,"text":"I'm more interested in the stories we tell about ourselves --"},{"time":753000,"text":"how as a writer, I find that African writers"},{"time":758000,"text":"have always been the curators of our humanity on this continent."},{"time":761000,"text":"The question is, how do I balance narratives that are wonderful"},{"time":767000,"text":"with narratives of wounds and self-loathing?"},{"time":771000,"text":"And this is the difficulty that I face."},{"time":774000,"text":"I am trying to move beyond political rhetoric"},{"time":776000,"text":"to a place of ethical questioning."},{"time":778000,"text":"I am asking us to balance the idea"},{"time":781000,"text":"of our complete vulnerability with the complete notion"},{"time":785000,"text":"of transformation of what is possible."}]},{"cues":[{"time":787000,"text":"As a young middle-class Nigerian activist,"},{"time":789000,"text":"I launched myself along with a whole generation of us"},{"time":792000,"text":"into the campaign to stop the government."},{"time":795000,"text":"And I asked millions of people,"},{"time":797000,"text":"without questioning my right to do so,"},{"time":799000,"text":"to go up against the government."},{"time":801000,"text":"And I watched them being locked up in prison and tear gassed."},{"time":803000,"text":"I justified it, and I said, \"This is the cost of revolution."},{"time":806000,"text":"Have I not myself been imprisoned?"},{"time":808000,"text":"Have I not myself been beaten?\""},{"time":810000,"text":"It wasn't until later, when I was imprisoned again,"},{"time":813000,"text":"that I understood the real meaning of torture,"},{"time":815000,"text":"and how easy your humanity can be taken from you,"},{"time":818000,"text":"for the time I was engaged in war,"},{"time":821000,"text":"righteous, righteous war."},{"time":824000,"text":"Excuse me."}]},{"cues":[{"time":827000,"text":"Sometimes I can stand before the world --"},{"time":829000,"text":"and when I say this, transformation"},{"time":831000,"text":"is a difficult and slow process --"},{"time":833000,"text":"sometimes I can stand before the world and say,"},{"time":836000,"text":"\"My name is Chris Abani."},{"time":838000,"text":"I have been human six days, but only sometimes.\""},{"time":841000,"text":"But this is a good thing."},{"time":843000,"text":"It's never going to be easy."},{"time":845000,"text":"There are no answers."},{"time":847000,"text":"As I was telling Rachel from Google Earth,"},{"time":849000,"text":"that I had challenged my students in America --"},{"time":851000,"text":"I said, \"You don't know anything about Africa, you're all idiots.\""},{"time":854000,"text":"And so they said, \"Tell me about Africa, Professor Abani.\""},{"time":857000,"text":"So I went to Google Earth and learned about Africa."},{"time":860000,"text":"And the truth be told, this is it, isn't it?"},{"time":863000,"text":"There are no essential Africans,"},{"time":864000,"text":"and most of us are as completely ignorant as everyone else"},{"time":866000,"text":"about the continent we come from,"},{"time":868000,"text":"and yet we want to make profound statements about it."},{"time":871000,"text":"And I think if we can just admit that we're all trying"},{"time":873000,"text":"to approximate the truth of our own communities,"},{"time":876000,"text":"it will make for a much more nuanced"},{"time":878000,"text":"and a much more interesting conversation."},{"time":881000,"text":"I want to believe that we can be agnostic about this,"},{"time":885000,"text":"that we can rise above all of this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":887000,"text":"When I was 10, I read James Baldwin's \"Another Country,\""},{"time":891000,"text":"and that book broke me."},{"time":893000,"text":"Not because I was encountering homosexual sex and love"},{"time":896000,"text":"for the first time, but because the way James wrote about it"},{"time":899000,"text":"made it impossible for me to attach otherness to it."},{"time":902000,"text":"\"Here,\" Jimmy said."},{"time":904000,"text":"\"Here is love, all of it.\""},{"time":906000,"text":"The fact that it happens in \"Another Country\""},{"time":908000,"text":"takes you quite by surprise."},{"time":911000,"text":"My friend Ronald Gottesman says there are three kinds of people in the world:"},{"time":913000,"text":"those who can count, and those who can't."},{"time":916000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":920000,"text":"He also says that the cause of all our trouble"},{"time":923000,"text":"is the belief in an essential, pure identity:"},{"time":926000,"text":"religious, ethnic, historical, ideological."}]},{"cues":[{"time":931000,"text":"I want to leave you with a poem by Yusef Komunyakaa"},{"time":934000,"text":"that speaks to transformation."},{"time":937000,"text":"It's called \"Ode to the Drum,\" and I'll try and read it"},{"time":940000,"text":"the way Yusef would be proud to hear it read."},{"time":946000,"text":"\"Gazelle, I killed you for your skin's exquisite touch,"},{"time":952000,"text":"for how easy it is to be nailed to a board"},{"time":955000,"text":"weathered raw as white butcher paper."},{"time":959000,"text":"Last night I heard my daughter praying for the meat here at my feet."},{"time":964000,"text":"You know it wasn't anger that made me stop my heart till the hammer fell."},{"time":968000,"text":"Weeks ago, you broke me as a woman"},{"time":971000,"text":"once shattered me into a song beneath her weight,"},{"time":975000,"text":"before you slouched into that grassy hush."},{"time":978000,"text":"And now I'm tightening lashes, shaped in hide as if around a ribcage,"},{"time":983000,"text":"shaped like five bowstrings."},{"time":985000,"text":"Ghosts cannot slip back inside the body's drum."},{"time":988000,"text":"You've been seasoned by wind, dusk and sunlight."},{"time":992000,"text":"Pressure can make everything whole again."},{"time":996000,"text":"Brass nails tacked into the ebony wood,"},{"time":998000,"text":"your face has been carved five times."},{"time":1001000,"text":"I have to drive trouble in the hills."},{"time":1003000,"text":"Trouble in the valley,"},{"time":1005000,"text":"and trouble by the river too."},{"time":1007000,"text":"There is no palm wine, fish, salt, or calabash."},{"time":1011000,"text":"Kadoom. Kadoom. Kadoom."},{"time":1015000,"text":"Ka-doooom."},{"time":1017000,"text":"Now I have beaten a song back into you."},{"time":1021000,"text":"Rise and walk away like a panther.\""},{"time":1025000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":1027000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}